-- в”Ђв”Ђ Qovery в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DevOps automation platform that lets engineering teams deploy, manage, and secure applications on their own cloud infrastructure, including AWS, GCP, and Azure, through a self-service internal developer platform, without needing dedicated DevOps expertise for every deployment.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Flat-rate, per-organization subscription with annual or monthly billing$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Team plan starts from $899 per month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Roughly 30-50 employees (as of 2026)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Paris, France$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Qovery Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Qovery review covering the DevOps automation and internal developer platform, its deployment features, pricing plans, pros, cons, and use cases.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Qovery is a DevOps automation platform founded in Paris, France in 2019 by Romaric Philogene (CEO), Pierre Mavro (CTO), and Morgan Perry, with the product launching publicly in 2020. The company builds what it describes as an internal developer platform that lets engineering teams deploy, observe, secure, and optimize applications directly on their own cloud infrastructure, including AWS, Google Cloud Platform, and Microsoft Azure, without requiring every team to have dedicated Kubernetes or DevOps expertise. Qovery has raised approximately $18 million in total funding across pre-seed, seed, and Series A rounds, including non-dilutive financing. Its most recent Series A round, announced in 2025, was $13 million led by IRIS Ventures with participation from Speedinvest, Crane Venture Partners, Techstars, Irregular Expressions, and angel investors including Datadog co-founders Olivier Pomel and Alexis Le-Quoc, Docker co-founder Sebastian Pahl, and Checkout.com CTO Ott Kaukver; the round valued Qovery at a post-money valuation of $45 million. The company reports growing at roughly 115 percent year over year and serving hundreds of client organizations and thousands of individual users. Functionally, Qovery sits between raw cloud infrastructure and application code, automating the provisioning of environments, managing infrastructure-as-code, and giving developers self-service deployment workflows so they can spin up and tear down environments, for example per-pull-request preview environments, without filing tickets to a central platform team. The product includes policy-as-code governance, managed Kubernetes cluster operations, deployment pipelines, and observability tooling, and it has recently added AI agent capabilities, with each paid seat including a corresponding AI agent seat for automating deployment and operations tasks. Pricing is flat-rate and per-organization rather than per-deployment: the Team plan starts from $899 per month and includes 10 human users plus 10 AI agent seats, two managed clusters, up to 100 environments, and 5,000 deployment minutes with business-hours support. The Business plan, Qovery's most popular tier, starts from $2,099 per month and includes 20 users and 20 AI agent seats with single sign-on, three managed clusters, up to 250 environments, 10,000 deployment minutes, a 99.9 percent uptime SLA, and policy-as-code governance. An Enterprise plan offers custom annual contracts with unlimited users and AI agent seats, on-premises or self-hosted deployment options, custom cluster counts, and 24/7 support with a dedicated customer success manager; additional AI agent seats beyond the included allotment cost $10 per month each. Qovery reports that customers see at least a 5x return on their investment through reduced DevOps engineering time. The platform is aimed primarily at engineering and platform teams at growth-stage and mid-market companies that want to standardize and self-serve cloud deployments without building an internal platform engineering team from scratch, and it competes with other internal developer platform and PaaS-style tools in the DevOps automation space.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '46c7eebc-d6a3-4c06-b0fb-74483d16333d';

