-- в”Ђв”Ђ QST в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Self-hosted, open-source assessment engine, released under GPLv2, for building quizzes, surveys, tests, and exams, with multi-tenancy, auto-grading, STEM equation support, and gradebook functionality for schools, training providers, and certification bodies.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open-source software (GPLv2 license); no license fees$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2018, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed (small, Canada-based independent software provider)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Canada (specific city not publicly disclosed)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$QST Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$QST review covering the open-source, self-hosted assessment platform for quizzes, surveys and exams, its features, licensing, pros, cons, and use cases.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$QST, short for Quiz/Survey/Test, is a free, open-source assessment platform built by QST Online Ltd., a Canada-based software provider that first released the software in 2018. The project describes itself as a complete, self-hosted assessment engine designed to give institutions full control over their exam and survey infrastructure rather than relying on a hosted vendor. QST installs on Windows 7, 10, and 11, Ubuntu Linux, and macOS, and it is built on a mod_perl and MySQL architecture that the project states can handle over 1,000 simultaneous test-takers on modest hardware, positioning it for high-concurrency use cases such as scheduled cohort exams. The software is distributed under the GNU General Public License version 2, which means it can be downloaded, run, modified, and even rebranded for commercial use without licensing fees or restrictions. QST supports a wide range of question types, including multiple-choice, matching, true/false, essay, and general survey questions, along with branching logic for adaptive assessments. It includes a built-in WYSIWYG equation editor supporting LaTeX and chemistry notation, making it suitable for STEM subjects where standard web forms fall short. Objective question types are auto-graded, while essay-style responses support manual grading, and results feed into an included gradebook module that lets instructors track marks across QST-based assessments and other assignments with custom weighting, functioning as a lightweight alternative to a full learning management system. A notable feature the project calls Memory temporarily displays study material to a test-taker once, after which they cannot return to review it, intended to test recall or discourage note-taking during an assessment. QST supports multi-tenancy, meaning a single server installation can serve multiple independent organizations, classes, and user groups, which is aimed at large educational institutions running many separate courses and instructors from one deployment rather than provisioning separate hosted accounts per department. The platform supports interoperability through import and export in QST's own XML format as well as Moodle XML, IMS QTI, Word XML, and PDF, easing migration to or from other assessment and LMS tools. Because QST is self-hosted, all student and assessment data stays on the operator's own infrastructure, which the project markets as aligned with GDPR and FERPA privacy expectations, and it reports zero publicly documented security vulnerabilities. According to the project, QST has been downloaded more than 26,000 times across over 185 countries since 2018. QST is best suited for schools, universities, training organizations, and certification bodies that want an on-premises, vendor-independent testing platform, particularly where large numbers of simultaneous test-takers, STEM notation, or strict data residency requirements make hosted assessment tools impractical.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '21d33fd5-20b2-4b49-8ccd-579b0f9edba6';

